# ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║  ServiceCycle — Environment Configuration                                        ║
# ║                                                                              ║
# ║  Copy this file to .env and fill in the values for your deployment.          ║
# ║  Lines starting with # are comments. Uncomment a line to activate it.        ║
# ║                                                                              ║
# ║  ServiceCycle is a self-hosted product. All features work with local storage      ║
# ║  and no cloud services. External services (S3, email, AI) are optional.     ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

# ── Required ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# PostgreSQL connection string.
#
# Pass-5 / Agent 3 (2026-05-17): the connection_limit + pool_timeout query
# params cap Prisma's per-process pool. Without them, Prisma defaults to
# `num_physical_cpus * 2 + 1`, which on a beefy laptop or CI box opens far
# more sockets than the demo droplet's Postgres (max_connections=100 default)
# can absorb under any concurrent multi-tenant load. 10 connections per
# server process leaves comfortable margin for the cron jobs + admin-tool
# ad-hoc queries that share the pool. `pool_timeout=30` gives a clear error
# within 30s if the pool is exhausted (default is silent stall). Self-host
# operators running a single replica can leave the defaults; multi-replica
# deployments should set explicit limits per replica.
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://USER:PASSWORD@localhost:5432/servicecycle?connection_limit=10&pool_timeout=30

# (B5) PostgreSQL credentials — required by docker-compose.yml.
# When you run ServiceCycle via `docker compose up`, the bundled Postgres service
# reads POSTGRES_PASSWORD (REQUIRED — compose refuses to start without it),
# POSTGRES_USER (default: servicecycle), and POSTGRES_DB (default: servicecycle) from
# this file. The `server` service builds its DATABASE_URL from these values,
# so the line above is only used when running the API outside Docker against
# an external Postgres.
#
# Set POSTGRES_PASSWORD to a long, random value — there is no recovery path
# if a public-internet Postgres is brute-forced. Treat it like a production
# DB credential, not a dev placeholder.
#   Generate: node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(24).toString('base64url'))"
#
# POSTGRES_PASSWORD=
# POSTGRES_USER=servicecycle
# POSTGRES_DB=servicecycle

# JWT signing secret — must be at least 32 characters, keep secret
# Generate: node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(48).toString('base64'))"
JWT_SECRET=change-me-to-a-long-random-string-at-least-32-chars

# ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │  MASTER_KEY — CRITICAL. READ THIS BEFORE DEPLOYING.                         │
# │                                                                              │
# │  MASTER_KEY is used to encrypt sensitive data stored in the database         │
# │  (API keys, TOTP secrets). If you enable document encryption (opt-in via     │
# │  Settings), it also becomes the root key for all stored documents.           │
# │                                                                              │
# │  ✗ If you lose MASTER_KEY, encrypted data is PERMANENTLY unrecoverable.     │
# │  ✗ ForgeRift LLC cannot help you recover it. No one can.                    │
# │  ✓ Back it up to a team password manager BEFORE starting the server.        │
# │  ✓ Never store the backup in the same place as your database backup.        │
# │                                                                              │
# │  Generate: node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('base64'))"
# └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
MASTER_KEY=

# ── Required in production ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

CLIENT_URL=https://your-servicecycle-domain.com

# ── Document Storage ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Where uploaded contract documents (PDFs, Word files, images) are stored.
# Local filesystem is the default — no cloud account required.
#
# In Docker, mount the storage directory as a host volume so files persist
# across container restarts and upgrades. Add to docker-compose.yml:
#   volumes:
#     - ./uploads:/app/uploads
#
# STORAGE_DEST=local            # local (default) | s3
# STORAGE_LOCAL_PATH=./uploads  # host path for local storage (via volume mount)
#
# S3-compatible cloud storage (only needed when STORAGE_DEST=s3).
# Works with AWS S3, Backblaze B2, Wasabi, Cloudflare R2, or a self-hosted
# MinIO instance on your own network:
#
# STORAGE_S3_BUCKET=my-servicecycle-documents
# STORAGE_S3_REGION=us-east-1
# STORAGE_S3_KEY_ID=AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE
# STORAGE_S3_SECRET=wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY
# STORAGE_S3_ENDPOINT=          # set for non-AWS, e.g. http://minio:9000

# ── Email ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# ServiceCycle sends transactional email for: password resets, user invites,
# alert digests, and backup failure notices.
#
# For local dev or installs without email: set EMAIL_MOCK=true to log emails
# to the console instead of sending them. All other email env vars are ignored.
#
# For production: provide a Brevo API key and a verified sender address.
# Sign up at resend.com (free tier: 3,000 emails/month).
#
# EMAIL_MOCK=true
# BREVO_API_KEY=re_xxxxxxxxxxxx
#
# EMAIL_FROM must match a domain verified in your Resend account.
# Example: EMAIL_FROM="ServiceCycle <noreply@yourdomain.com>"
# EMAIL_FROM=
#
# FEEDBACK_ENABLED is the master switch for the in-product feedback feature.
# Resolution rule (operator-friendly):
#   - If FEEDBACK_ENABLED is explicitly set to 'true' or 'false', that wins.
#   - Otherwise the default depends on DEMO_MODE:
#       DEMO_MODE=true  -> feedback ON  (demo operators want feedback flowing)
#       DEMO_MODE=false -> feedback OFF (self-hosted customers opt in deliberately)
# Self-hosted customers running ServiceCycle in production therefore start with
# feedback OFF by default - matching the EULA S5 carve-out language - and
# must affirmatively set FEEDBACK_ENABLED=true to receive in-product feedback.
# Demo operators (DEMO_MODE=true) get feedback ON automatically; this is
# disclosed to demo visitors via the Demo Sandbox Notice and via an inline
# notice on the feedback button itself.
# Default-OFF: feedback is silently discarded unless you explicitly set
# FEEDBACK_ENABLED=true. This matches the EULA §5 carve-out, which says
# the feature can be disabled by setting FEEDBACK_ENABLED=false (and
# documents the operator's affirmative opt-in). Required for any feedback
# email to be sent regardless of SUPPORT_EMAIL / BREVO_API_KEY.
# FEEDBACK_ENABLED=false
#
# SUPPORT_EMAIL is where in-app feedback submissions are delivered.
# Leave unset (or leave FEEDBACK_ENABLED unset) to silently discard
# feedback. Both must be configured for feedback to reach an inbox.
# SUPPORT_EMAIL=it@yourcompany.com
#
# (L4) On the ServiceCycle demo box specifically, set:
#   FEEDBACK_ENABLED=true
#   SUPPORT_EMAIL=demofeedback@servicecycle.app
# A Cloudflare Email Routing alias forwards demofeedback@servicecycle.app →
# claudedussy@gmail.com so feedback lands in Dustin's inbox. Subjects
# starting with "[ServiceCycle Feedback]" bypass the EMAIL_MOCK gate even when
# DEMO_MODE forces it on; see lib/email.js sendEmail() for the bypass.
# Requires BREVO_API_KEY + EMAIL_FROM to be configured on the demo box.

# ── Slack ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# OPTIONAL. Posts the nightly alert digest into a Slack channel using an
# incoming webhook. Per-account configuration lives in Settings → Alerts in
# the UI; the env vars below are a self-hosted fallback for operators who'd
# rather wire it up once at the host level.
#
# Create a webhook in Slack: Apps → Incoming Webhooks → Add to Slack.
# Only https://hooks.slack.com/services/ URLs are accepted (SSRF defense).
#
# SLACK_ENABLED=false
# SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL=https://hooks.slack.com/services/T.../B.../...
#
# Set SLACK_MOCK=true to log Slack payloads to the console instead of
# sending them — handy for local dev and CI.
# SLACK_MOCK=false

# ── Microsoft Teams ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# OPTIONAL. Same model as Slack above — per-account incoming webhook posts
# the nightly alert digest into a Teams channel. UI configuration lives at
# Settings → Alerts; the env vars below are a host-level fallback.
#
# Add an incoming webhook to a Teams channel: Channel → Manage channel →
# Connectors → Incoming Webhook → Configure.
# Only Microsoft-hosted webhook URLs are accepted (outlook.office.com,
# outlook.office365.com, or *.webhook.office.com) — SSRF defense.
#
# TEAMS_ENABLED=false
# TEAMS_WEBHOOK_URL=https://<tenant>.webhook.office.com/webhookb2/...
#
# Set TEAMS_MOCK=true to log Teams payloads to the console instead of
# sending them.
# TEAMS_MOCK=false

# ── AI / LLM Provider ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Powers contract field extraction, renewal brief generation, Ask ServiceCycle
# chat, and news classification. Set AI_ENABLED=false to run ServiceCycle without
# an AI provider — manual contract entry still works, AI features turn off.
#
# v0.35.0 (May 2026): the demo defaults to Cloudflare Workers AI as the
# primary provider, with HuggingFace + Groq as the fallback chain for chat +
# classification. Extraction + brief stay on Cloudflare (Mistral Small 3.1
# 24B) only — the cascade is too quality-degrading on those high-value
# paths. Self-host customers may bring their own provider (any of the
# supported list below) and self-host has UNLIMITED quotas + no monthly
# spend cap.
#
# AI_ENABLED=true
# AI_PROVIDER=cloudflare         # cloudflare (v0.35.0) | anthropic | openai | azure_openai | gemini
# AI_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
#
# Cloudflare Workers AI (v0.35.0 — demo default):
# CF_WORKERS_AI_ACCOUNT_ID=<cloudflare-account-uuid>
# CF_WORKERS_AI_API_KEY=<workers-ai-token; separate from your regular CF api token>
# Request timeout for CF Workers AI calls, in milliseconds. Default 30000.
# Bump if you see TimeoutError on brief / extract under load (mistral-small
# on a long per-category template + Tavily context can need 20-25s). Values
# below 1000 are coerced back to the default.
# CF_WORKERS_AI_TIMEOUT_MS=30000
#
# HuggingFace Inference (cascade fallback #1 for chat + classification only):
# HF_TOKEN=hf_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
# HF_MODEL=meta-llama/Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct   # optional override; default shown
#
# Groq Cloud (cascade fallback #2 for chat + classification only):
# GROQ_API_KEY=gsk_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
# GROQ_MODEL=llama-3.1-8b-instant             # optional override; default shown
#
# Disable a provider mid-day without restarting (operator kill-switch):
# AI_DISABLED_PROVIDERS=                       # comma-separated, e.g. "groq,huggingface"
#
# Azure OpenAI (use instead of AI_API_KEY when AI_PROVIDER=azure_openai):
# AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT=https://your-resource.openai.azure.com/
# AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY=
# AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT=
#
# Vision (image extraction) routing when AI_PROVIDER=cloudflare:
# Cloudflare's Mistral/Llama text models don't expose unified vision; vision
# falls back to AI_VISION_PROVIDER (default anthropic). Operators who want
# zero Anthropic dependency on demo can set this to 'gemini' instead.
# AI_VISION_PROVIDER=anthropic

# ── AI Daily Caps (per-user, per-day) ────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Self-host default: UNLIMITED. These vars only matter on a shared instance
# where you want to cap per-user AI burn (the public demo at servicecycle.app
# uses these to control credit spend on a shared key).
#
# v0.35.0 demo defaults (locked per legal-pass-2026-05-17 D1):
#   AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER_EXTRACT=1     # contract extraction is high-value
#   AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER_BRIEF=3       # renewal brief regeneration
#   AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER_ASK=10        # Ask ServiceCycle conversational
#   AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER_BRIEF_SEARCH=3  # Tavily web-search enrichment
#
# Each cap accepts a non-negative integer. Set to 0 or omit to disable that
# specific cap. AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER (no suffix) is the uniform fallback.
#
# AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER=                 # uniform fallback (any action)
# AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER_EXTRACT=         # PDF/image ingest + signature shared
# AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER_ASK=             # Ask ServiceCycle assistant
# AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER_BRIEF=           # Renewal brief generation
# AI_DAILY_CAP_PER_USER_BRIEF_SEARCH=    # Tavily web-search enrichment

# ── Renewal brief output budget ────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Max output tokens per renewal brief generation. The structured 4-section
# output (Situation / Market / Tactics / Watch For) typically lands at
# ~700-800 words; the value below is safety margin so the final section
# doesn't truncate mid-sentence under unusual circumstances.
#
# Auto-defaults when unset:
#   - DEMO_MODE=true   : 1800 tokens  (cost-protected on shared API key)
#   - DEMO_MODE=false  : 2250 tokens  (more headroom for complex contracts;
#                                       customer paying their own AI cost)
# Set explicitly to override either default.
#
# AI_BRIEF_MAX_TOKENS=

# ── Tavily Web Search (optional, Phase 4) ────────────────────────────────────
#
# When set, the renewal brief's Market section is enriched with category-
# specific web search results from the per-template domain allowlist
# (lib/aiBrief/templates/*.js). Brief still generates without enrichment
# when this key is missing — the template's no-reference fallback fires.
#
# Get a key from https://tavily.com/ (their free tier covers occasional
# self-host use; volume needs a paid plan).
#
# TAVILY_API_KEY=tvly-...


# === Demo-mode budget guards (lib/aiBudgetGuard.js) ==========================
#
# Process-wide budgets for paid external APIs the demo instance depends on.
# Active only when DEMO_MODE=true; no-op on self-host.
#
# Two tracking shapes coexist:
#
#   1. Per-UTC-DAY call counters — used for gemini, tavily, brevo, huggingface,
#      groq. Hard ceiling per day; rolls over at 00:00 UTC. Set to 0 (or
#      negative) to DISABLE the cap for that service.
#
#   2. Per-UTC-MONTH $-and-Neuron tracker (v0.35.0) — used for Cloudflare
#      Workers AI specifically because WAI is billed in Neurons and the
#      $25/mo cap is the operative ceiling. Rolls over at 00:00 UTC on the
#      1st of each month (server/index.js cron). Alerts via Brevo at
#      AI_BUDGET_ALERT_PCT (default 75%) and hard-stops further CF calls at
#      AI_BUDGET_HARDSTOP_PCT (default 90%) — both percentages of
#      AI_BUDGET_MONTHLY_USD.
#
# Daily counters:
# GEMINI_DAILY_CALL_BUDGET=1300        # default 1300 (Gemini Flash free is 1500/day; legacy)
# TAVILY_DAILY_CALL_BUDGET=30          # default 30   (Tavily free is 1000/MONTH)
# BREVO_DAILY_CALL_BUDGET=50           # default 50   (Brevo free is 300/day)
# HUGGINGFACE_DAILY_CALL_BUDGET=1000   # default 1000 (HF Inference free; cascade-only)
# GROQ_DAILY_CALL_BUDGET=500           # default 500  (Groq dev-tier; cascade-only)
#
# Cloudflare Workers AI monthly $-cap (v0.35.0):
# AI_BUDGET_MONTHLY_USD=25             # default 25 ($5 CF Workers Paid base + $20 overage)
# AI_BUDGET_ALERT_PCT=75               # default 75 (Brevo alert at $18.75 effective)
# AI_BUDGET_HARDSTOP_PCT=90            # default 90 (refuse further CF calls at $22.50 effective)

# ── Vendor News Scanner ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Polls public RSS feeds every 6 hours and matches articles to your vendors.
# Makes outbound HTTP requests to ~30 public news sources (TechCrunch, etc.).
#
# Set to false for air-gapped deployments or environments with strict
# outbound network policies.
#
# NEWS_SCANNER_ENABLED=true

# ── Automated Backups ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Daily pg_dump at 2:00 AM server time.
# Local filesystem is the default — no cloud account required.
#
# In Docker, mount the backup directory as a host volume:
#   volumes:
#     - ./backups:/app/backups
#
# BACKUP_DEST=local            # local (default) | s3 | both
# BACKUP_LOCAL_PATH=./backups  # host path (via volume mount in Docker)
# BACKUP_RETENTION_DAYS=30     # delete backups older than N days (default: 30)
#
# S3-compatible cloud storage (only needed when BACKUP_DEST=s3 or both).
# Works with AWS S3, Backblaze B2, Wasabi, MinIO, or any on-prem S3-compatible
# store (e.g. a self-hosted MinIO instance on the same LAN):
#
# BACKUP_S3_BUCKET=my-servicecycle-backups
# BACKUP_S3_REGION=us-east-1
# BACKUP_S3_KEY_ID=AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE
# BACKUP_S3_SECRET=wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY
# BACKUP_S3_ENDPOINT=          # set for non-AWS, e.g. http://minio:9000 or
#                              # https://s3.us-west-004.backblazeb2.com
#
# DigitalOcean Spaces example (drop-in S3-compatible target — recommended
# for ForgeRift-hosted demo and for self-host operators on DigitalOcean):
#
#   BACKUP_DEST=s3
#   BACKUP_S3_BUCKET=servicecycle-backups
#   BACKUP_S3_REGION=nyc3                # or sfo3 / ams3 / sgp1 / fra1 / blr1
#   BACKUP_S3_KEY_ID=DO00xxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#   BACKUP_S3_SECRET=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#   BACKUP_S3_ENDPOINT=https://nyc3.digitaloceanspaces.com
#
# Issued via DO console → API → Spaces Keys → Generate New Key. Spaces
# uses the same S3 API surface, so no ServiceCycle code changes are needed.

# ── Optional / Advanced ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# JWT access token lifetime (default: 1h)
# JWT_EXPIRES_IN=1h

# Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy header (default: same-site).
# Set to cross-origin when frontend and API are on different eTLD+1 domains.
# CORP_POLICY=cross-origin

# Open self-registration (default: false — users come through the invite flow).
# Set to 'true' only when provisioning a brand-new self-hosted instance.
# Note: the first-run wizard at /setup creates the initial admin without
# needing this — REGISTRATION_OPEN is only for subsequent self-serve signups.
# REGISTRATION_OPEN=false

# (B1, N9) Reverse-proxy awareness.
# TRUST_PROXY tells Express which X-Forwarded-For entries to trust when
# resolving the real client IP. Required for accurate per-IP rate limiting
# and audit-log attribution behind any reverse proxy.
#
# Three forms are supported (in order of preference):
#
#   A. CIDR allowlist (RECOMMENDED for production).
#      Comma-separated list of CIDRs / IPs Express should trust as
#      legitimate proxy hops. Express walks X-Forwarded-For right-to-left
#      and only trusts entries originating from listed networks; the first
#      non-listed hop is treated as the real client. Structurally blocks
#      X-Forwarded-For chain spoofing because forged entries from outside
#      the allowlist are ignored.
#
#      For Cloudflare-fronted deployments, run
#         bash scripts/get-trust-proxy-cidrs.sh
#      to print a paste-ready string with current CF v4+v6 ranges plus
#      127.0.0.1 and Docker bridge subnets.
#
#      Example (truncated; the script emits the full list):
#      TRUST_PROXY=127.0.0.1, 172.16.0.0/12, 173.245.48.0/20, 103.21.244.0/22
#
#   B. Legacy boolean (kept for backward compat).
#      TRUST_PROXY=true makes Express trust ONE upstream hop. Equivalent
#      to the original setting; logs a deprecation warning at startup
#      because it does NOT distinguish between legitimate and spoofed
#      X-Forwarded-For entries. Acceptable when the firewall absolutely
#      guarantees nothing can reach the reverse proxy bypassing the front
#      end (rare).
#
#   C. Default (unset / empty / 'false').
#      No trust. req.ip is the connecting socket address. Use only when
#      ServiceCycle is directly internet-exposed with NO proxy in front of it.
#
# WARNING: never enable forms A or B on a directly-internet-exposed
# instance without firewall rules that prevent direct access to the
# reverse proxy. Untrusted clients can otherwise spoof X-Forwarded-For
# to bypass per-IP rate limits and inject fake IPs into your audit log.
# See docs/install.md for multi-proxy chain configuration — required for accurate rate limiting and audit
# logging behind a proxy.
#
# WARNING: never enable this on a directly-internet-exposed instance.
# Untrusted clients can spoof X-Forwarded-For to bypass per-IP rate limits
# and inject fake IPs into your audit log. See docs/install.md for multi-
# proxy chain configuration.
# TRUST_PROXY=true

# (B2) ActivityLog retention. The audit log table grows by every contract
# update, login failure, permission denial, and document access. A daily cron
# at 03:00 server time deletes rows older than this many days. Default: 365.
# Lower to 90 or 30 for high-volume tenants where audit-log size dominates
# pg_dump time. Setting an unreasonably small value is allowed but will
# permanently delete history that may be needed for compliance review.
# ACTIVITY_LOG_RETENTION_DAYS=365

# (B1 5/02) BackupLog retention. Each backup attempt (cron or manual) writes
# a row to backup_logs with status, filename, size, and any error message.
# A daily cron at 03:15 server time deletes rows older than this many days.
# Default: 180. The backup files themselves expire under your storage policy
# (local 30 days by default, or whatever you configure on S3); this controls
# only the audit row. Lower to 30/60 if you only care about recent failures;
# raise if you need a longer audit trail for compliance.
# BACKUP_LOG_RETENTION_DAYS=180

# Encrypt nightly pg_dump.gz files at rest with AES-256-GCM. Default ON
# (enabled when MASTER_KEY is present, which it must be for the server to
# boot). Files written with magic header LBKE0001 + IV + auth tag, suffix
# .sql.gz.enc. Restore via `node scripts/decrypt-backup.js <file>`. Set to
# 'false' only for offline restore exercises; the unencrypted .sql.gz on
# disk contains every row of customer data.
# BACKUP_ENCRYPT=true

# ── Better Stack (Logtail) log shipping ───────────────────────────────────────
#
# Optional structured-log shipping to Better Stack Telemetry. Off by default —
# only kicks in when both BETTERSTACK_INGEST_URL and BETTERSTACK_SOURCE_TOKEN
# are set. The shipper batches log lines and POSTs them as Bearer-auth JSON to
# the ingest host. Add the https:// scheme; the host alone won't work.
#
# Get a Source token at https://telemetry.betterstack.com/ → Sources → Connect.
# The Sources UI gives you a `s12345.{region}.betterstackdata.com` host —
# prepend https:// for the URL value below.
#
# BETTERSTACK_INGEST_URL=https://s12345.us-east-1.betterstackdata.com
# BETTERSTACK_SOURCE_TOKEN=your_source_token_here
# BETTERSTACK_DEBUG=false   # set 'true' to log every send to stdout (noisy)

# ── Healthchecks.io cron heartbeats ───────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Optional. When set, every scheduled cron (nightly backup, alertEngine,
# nightlySync, *Prune, etc.) pings Healthchecks.io with start / success /
# fail signals. A silently-stopped scheduler alarms within minutes instead
# of weeks-later when a customer notices a missed renewal alert.
#
# Two configuration styles:
#
#   1. Project Ping Key (recommended — scales as you add crons):
#      Healthchecks auto-provisions a check per cron name on first ping.
#      HEALTHCHECKS_PING_KEY=your_32_char_project_ping_key
#
#   2. Per-check UUIDs (overrides the project key for a single cron):
#      HEALTHCHECKS_URL_BACKUP=https://hc-ping.com/<uuid>
#      HEALTHCHECKS_URL_ALERTENGINE=https://hc-ping.com/<uuid>
#      (Env var name is HEALTHCHECKS_URL_ + cron name uppercased; full list
#      is in server/lib/heartbeat.js.) These are NOT in the compose whitelist
#      by default — add explicit entries to docker-compose.ghcr.yml if you
#      use this style.
#
# HEALTHCHECKS_DEBUG=false   # set 'true' to log every ping (noisy)

# ── Demo Mode ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# DEMO_MODE=true puts the running instance into a constrained sandbox suitable
# for public sales demos and recorded walkthroughs:
#
#   - EMAIL_MOCK is forced true (no real emails ever sent, regardless of
#     BREVO_API_KEY value)
#   - AI_ENABLED is forced false (no LLM calls — protects API credits and
#     prevents leaking real document content into a third-party API during
#     demos)
#   - REGISTRATION_OPEN is forced true (visitors can self-serve a sandbox)
#   - A nightly cron at 03:30 server time wipes all data in the demo account
#     and re-runs scripts/seed-demo.js, so each morning visitors land in a
#     coherent freshly-populated sandbox
#
# Default credentials produced by seed-demo.js:
#   admin@demo.local      / Admin1234!
#   manager@demo.local    / Manager1234!
#   viewer@demo.local     / Viewer1234!
#   consultant@demo.local / Consultant1234!
#
# DEMO_MODE=false

# ── Stripe Billing (Sprint 6 — opt-in, SaaS-only) ─────────────────────────────
#
# ServiceCycle supports two business models that share the same data model:
#
#   - planType=licensed (self-hosted): The customer owns the install and pays
#     a perpetual or annual license out of band. Stripe is OFF, tier
#     enforcement is bypassed, and these env vars stay unset.
#
#   - planType=saas (Anthropic-operated demo or hosted): A managed instance
#     where access is gated behind a Stripe subscription. Set STRIPE_ENABLED=true
#     and configure the keys + price IDs below.
#
# This section is the *seam* — schema columns, helper module, and middleware
# are in place, but the actual Checkout flow + webhook handler are deferred
# until the first paying customer. See docs/stripe-integration.md for the
# remaining slot-in tasks.
#
# Get keys at https://dashboard.stripe.com/apikeys (test keys begin with sk_test_).
# STRIPE_ENABLED=false
# STRIPE_SECRET_KEY=sk_test_replace_me
# STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET=whsec_replace_me

# Price IDs from your Stripe dashboard. The three tiers map onto the existing
# PlanTier enum (small / mid / enterprise). Leave blank if you don't sell
# that tier.
# STRIPE_PRICE_ID_SMALL=
# STRIPE_PRICE_ID_MID=
# STRIPE_PRICE_ID_ENTERPRISE=

# ── v0.68.2 (audit Low Quick Wins) -- refresh token tuning ─────────────
# REFRESH_TOKEN_TTL_DAYS: how long a refresh token stays valid.
# Default 30 days. Lower for higher-security tenancy; higher for less-
# frequently-active users. Bounded [1, 365].
# REFRESH_TOKEN_TTL_DAYS=30

# REFRESH_TOKEN_PER_USER_CAP: max active refresh tokens per user. New
# logins beyond the cap evict the oldest active token. Default 10.
# Bounded [1, 100].
# REFRESH_TOKEN_PER_USER_CAP=10

# ── Enterprise SSO + SCIM via self-hosted Ory Polis (feature/sso-polis) ───────
#
# ServiceCycle is the OAuth relying party; Ory Polis (Apache-2.0) is the broker
# brokering corporate SAML/OIDC IdPs behind one OAuth 2.1 (Auth Code + PKCE)
# flow + SCIM 2.0 directory sync. Polis runs as a SEPARATE container/process on
# our Postgres (see docs/security/SSO_DESIGN.md + the docker-compose addition).
#
# SSO_ENABLED is the master switch (default false). When true, the server
# REFUSES TO BOOT unless POLIS_BASE_URL, POLIS_API_KEY, SCIM_WEBHOOK_SECRET, and
# SSO_CALLBACK_URL are all set (fail closed + loud — see lib/ssoConfig.ts).
# SSO is ALSO gated per-account behind the `sso` AccountSetting feature flag, so
# it ships dark and is enabled per customer.
# SSO_ENABLED=false

# Internal base URL the API uses to call Polis (token / userinfo / admin API).
# POLIS_BASE_URL=http://polis:5225

# Public base URL the BROWSER is redirected to for /oauth/authorize, if it
# differs from POLIS_BASE_URL (e.g. behind a reverse proxy). Defaults to
# POLIS_BASE_URL when unset.
# POLIS_EXTERNAL_URL=https://sso.servicecycle.app

# Polis admin API key (server-only; provisions connections/directories).
# Must match one of Polis's own API_KEYS. NEVER commit a real value.
# POLIS_API_KEY=replace_me_with_a_long_random_string

# Polis product identifier for this app (namespaces connections). Default
# 'servicecycle'.
# POLIS_PRODUCT=servicecycle

# Our OAuth redirect_uri. MUST match the redirectUrl registered on the Polis
# connection. Points at GET /api/sso/callback.
# SSO_CALLBACK_URL=https://app.servicecycle.app/api/sso/callback

# HMAC secret used to verify inbound SCIM webhooks (Polis BoxyHQ-Signature:
# t=<ms>,s=<hmacSHA256hex>). Must equal the webhook secret configured on the
# Polis directory. Missing => SCIM webhook fails closed.
# SCIM_WEBHOOK_SECRET=replace_me_with_a_long_random_string

# Allow login-time (JIT) user creation when an SSO user has no SCIM record yet.
# Default false (SCIM-provisioned users only). JIT users default to role
# `viewer` and are never auto-granted admin/oem_admin.
# SSO_JIT_PROVISIONING=false

# Timeout (ms) for outbound calls to Polis. Default 8000. Bounded >= 1000.
# POLIS_TIMEOUT_MS=8000
